{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01T8JLyjhTG7wwHAuGDCUU3A","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Y74TChkEtxAboKZ5RBELwd","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/REVIEW.md","content":"# Code Review: CLI Support\n\n## Summary\n\nThe CLI implementation is well-structured and covers the core use cases described in the task: interactive card creation, listing, viewing, moving, deleting, and fuzzy search. The `kanbamd` binary entry point is correctly wired in `package.json`, chalk is used throughout for colored output, and the README documents all commands clearly.\n\n**Verdict: not approved** — two issues require fixes before merging: a phantom dependency (`@inquirer/core` not declared in `package.json`) and missing column-name validation in the `init` command that allows path traversal.\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n### 1. Phantom dependency: `@inquirer/core` (Critical)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:7`\n\n```typescript\nimport { ExitPromptError } from \"@inquirer/core\"\n```\n\n`@inquirer/core` is not listed in `package.json` as a direct dependency. It is only present in `node_modules` because it is a transitive dependency of the individual `@inquirer/*` packages. In strict package managers (pnpm with `hoist=false`, Yarn PnP, Yarn Berry) only explicitly declared dependencies are resolvable at runtime. This import will fail silently in those environments.\n\n**Fix:** Add `@inquirer/core` as an explicit dependency in `package.json`, or alternatively import `ExitPromptError` from one of the already-declared `@inquirer/prompts` components if they re-export it.\n\n---\n\n### 2. No column-name validation in `init` — allows path traversal (High)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:183–199`\n\n```typescript\nconst columns = columnsRaw\n  .split(\",\")\n  .map((c) => c.trim())\n  .filter(Boolean)\n...\nfor (const col of columns) {\n  await mkdir(path.join(root, col), { recursive: true })\n}\n```\n\nThe `init` command writes directories without calling `validateColumnName()`. Passing `--columns 'todo,../evil'` causes `mkdir(path.join(root, '../evil'))`, creating a directory outside the intended root. The same validation used in the `Kanbamd` constructor should be applied here.\n\n**Fix:** Call `validateColumnName(col)` inside the loop before `mkdir`.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Wrong error type in `validateColumnName` (Medium)\n\n**File:** `src/helpers.ts:33`\n\n```typescript\nthrow new InvalidFrontmatterError(`Invalid column name: ${column}`)\n```\n\nColumn name validation has nothing to do with frontmatter. Throwing `InvalidFrontmatterError` here makes error handling confusing for callers that want to distinguish column errors from frontmatter errors. There is no dedicated `InvalidColumnNameError`, so `ColumnNotFoundError` is a better fit, or a new error class could be added.\n\n**Fix:** Change the thrown error to `ColumnNotFoundError` or introduce an `InvalidColumnNameError extends KanbamdError` in `errors.ts`.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Order validator accepts `0` but error message says \"positive integer\" (Low)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:303–309`\n\n```typescript\nvalidate: (v) =>\n  !v.trim() || /^\\d+$/.test(v.trim())\n    ? true\n    : \"Must be a positive integer\",\n```\n\nThe regex `/^\\d+$/` matches `\"0\"`, which is not a positive integer. Entering `0` is silently treated as order 1 (first position) because of `Math.max(0, parseInt(\"0\", 10) - 1) === 0`. The UX is confusing: the message promises positive integers but `0` is accepted and produces an unexpected result.\n\n**Fix:** Change the regex to `/^[1-9]\\d*$/` so that `0` is rejected with a clear message.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `findConfigPath` unnecessarily declared `async` (Low)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:24`\n\n```typescript\nasync function findConfigPath(startDir: string): Promise<string | null> {\n```\n\nThe function body only uses `existsSync` (synchronous) and `path.dirname` (synchronous). There are no `await` expressions inside it. The `async` keyword adds an unnecessary Promise wrapper and misleads readers into thinking there is I/O.\n\n**Fix:** Remove the `async` keyword and return type `Promise<string | null>` → `string | null`.\n\n---\n\n### 6. No `edit`/`update` command in CLI (Low)\n\nThe library exposes `updateCard` (title, body, tags) but the CLI has no corresponding command. Once a card is created, its content can only be changed by editing the markdown file manually. This is a completeness gap that will be noticed by users.\n\n---\n\n### 7. Multi-line body not supported in `add` prompt (Low)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:289–292`\n\nThe `input()` prompt captures a single line. Users cannot add a multi-line body from the CLI without editing the file afterward. The README does not mention this limitation.\n\n---\n\n## What Works Well\n\n- **Architecture**: clear separation between `init`, board resolution, and command actions.\n- **Interactive fallback**: every command that accepts an optional `[id]` falls back to an interactive `select` picker — consistent and user-friendly.\n- **Global options**: `--root` and `--columns` override config discovery uniformly across all commands.\n- **Error handling**: `ExitPromptError` is caught and handled gracefully (Ctrl-C shows \"Cancelled.\" and exits 0).\n- **README**: CLI section is thorough — quick start, config file explanation, and a full command reference table.\n- **Chalk usage**: color output is readable and informative (column names in cyan, tags in yellow, success in green, errors in red).\n- **`init` command**: writes `.kanbamd.json` and creates column directories in one step, with good default columns.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":177,"cache_read_input_tokens":45569,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":177},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7e10c329-12dd-4922-8869-d58b7dccb0a3","uuid":"48929b62-79ef-424b-86e3-d9af8c143a90"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Y74TChkEtxAboKZ5RBELwd","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /workspace/REVIEW.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7e10c329-12dd-4922-8869-d58b7dccb0a3","uuid":"bddec5d3-efae-47d2-acc4-f91304af8f23","timestamp":"2026-05-03T16:59:07.701Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/workspace/REVIEW.md","content":"# Code Review: CLI Support\n\n## Summary\n\nThe CLI implementation is well-structured and covers the core use cases described in the task: interactive card creation, listing, viewing, moving, deleting, and fuzzy search. The `kanbamd` binary entry point is correctly wired in `package.json`, chalk is used throughout for colored output, and the README documents all commands clearly.\n\n**Verdict: not approved** — two issues require fixes before merging: a phantom dependency (`@inquirer/core` not declared in `package.json`) and missing column-name validation in the `init` command that allows path traversal.\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n### 1. Phantom dependency: `@inquirer/core` (Critical)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:7`\n\n```typescript\nimport { ExitPromptError } from \"@inquirer/core\"\n```\n\n`@inquirer/core` is not listed in `package.json` as a direct dependency. It is only present in `node_modules` because it is a transitive dependency of the individual `@inquirer/*` packages. In strict package managers (pnpm with `hoist=false`, Yarn PnP, Yarn Berry) only explicitly declared dependencies are resolvable at runtime. This import will fail silently in those environments.\n\n**Fix:** Add `@inquirer/core` as an explicit dependency in `package.json`, or alternatively import `ExitPromptError` from one of the already-declared `@inquirer/prompts` components if they re-export it.\n\n---\n\n### 2. No column-name validation in `init` — allows path traversal (High)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:183–199`\n\n```typescript\nconst columns = columnsRaw\n  .split(\",\")\n  .map((c) => c.trim())\n  .filter(Boolean)\n...\nfor (const col of columns) {\n  await mkdir(path.join(root, col), { recursive: true })\n}\n```\n\nThe `init` command writes directories without calling `validateColumnName()`. Passing `--columns 'todo,../evil'` causes `mkdir(path.join(root, '../evil'))`, creating a directory outside the intended root. The same validation used in the `Kanbamd` constructor should be applied here.\n\n**Fix:** Call `validateColumnName(col)` inside the loop before `mkdir`.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Wrong error type in `validateColumnName` (Medium)\n\n**File:** `src/helpers.ts:33`\n\n```typescript\nthrow new InvalidFrontmatterError(`Invalid column name: ${column}`)\n```\n\nColumn name validation has nothing to do with frontmatter. Throwing `InvalidFrontmatterError` here makes error handling confusing for callers that want to distinguish column errors from frontmatter errors. There is no dedicated `InvalidColumnNameError`, so `ColumnNotFoundError` is a better fit, or a new error class could be added.\n\n**Fix:** Change the thrown error to `ColumnNotFoundError` or introduce an `InvalidColumnNameError extends KanbamdError` in `errors.ts`.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Order validator accepts `0` but error message says \"positive integer\" (Low)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:303–309`\n\n```typescript\nvalidate: (v) =>\n  !v.trim() || /^\\d+$/.test(v.trim())\n    ? true\n    : \"Must be a positive integer\",\n```\n\nThe regex `/^\\d+$/` matches `\"0\"`, which is not a positive integer. Entering `0` is silently treated as order 1 (first position) because of `Math.max(0, parseInt(\"0\", 10) - 1) === 0`. The UX is confusing: the message promises positive integers but `0` is accepted and produces an unexpected result.\n\n**Fix:** Change the regex to `/^[1-9]\\d*$/` so that `0` is rejected with a clear message.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `findConfigPath` unnecessarily declared `async` (Low)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:24`\n\n```typescript\nasync function findConfigPath(startDir: string): Promise<string | null> {\n```\n\nThe function body only uses `existsSync` (synchronous) and `path.dirname` (synchronous). There are no `await` expressions inside it. The `async` keyword adds an unnecessary Promise wrapper and misleads readers into thinking there is I/O.\n\n**Fix:** Remove the `async` keyword and return type `Promise<string | null>` → `string | null`.\n\n---\n\n### 6. No `edit`/`update` command in CLI (Low)\n\nThe library exposes `updateCard` (title, body, tags) but the CLI has no corresponding command. Once a card is created, its content can only be changed by editing the markdown file manually. This is a completeness gap that will be noticed by users.\n\n---\n\n### 7. Multi-line body not supported in `add` prompt (Low)\n\n**File:** `src/cli.ts:289–292`\n\nThe `input()` prompt captures a single line. Users cannot add a multi-line body from the CLI without editing the file afterward. The README does not mention this limitation.\n\n---\n\n## What Works Well\n\n- **Architecture**: clear separation between `init`, board resolution, and command actions.\n- **Interactive fallback**: every command that accepts an optional `[id]` falls back to an interactive `select` picker — consistent and user-friendly.\n- **Global options**: `--root` and `--columns` override config discovery uniformly across all commands.\n- **Error handling**: `ExitPromptError` is caught and handled gracefully (Ctrl-C shows \"Cancelled.\" and exits 0).\n- **README**: CLI section is thorough — quick start, config file explanation, and a full command reference table.\n- **Chalk usage**: color output is readable and informative (column names in cyan, tags in yellow, success in green, errors in red).\n- **`init` command**: writes `.kanbamd.json` and creates column directories in one step, with good default columns.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
